On Team stats, for gf and ga hsould you use away and home stats and not overall
When evaluating team statistics, it's essential to consider the home and away splits for goals for (GF) and goals against (GA). This is because teams often perform differently at home versus on the road.
Using Home and Away Splits
Instead of using overall GF and GA statistics, you can use the home and away splits to get a more accurate picture. For example:
For the Florida Panthers (FLA) playing at home:
Home GF: 3.5 goals per game
Home GA: 2.7 goals per game
For the Washington Capitals (WSH) playing away:
Away GF: 2.9 goals per game
Away GA: 3.1 goals per game
By using these home and away splits, you can get a better sense of how each team performs in different environments. This can help you make more informed decisions when evaluating their chances of scoring.
Updated Rating System
Here's an updated version of the rating system that incorporates home and away splits:
Team Statistics (40%)
Home/Away GF: Weighted average of home and away goals for per game.
Home/Away GA: Weighted average of home and away goals against per game.
PP%: Power play percentage.
PK%: Penalty kill percentage.
Game-Specific Factors (30%)
Head-to-Head: Recent head-to-head matchups between the two teams.
Home/Away Advantage: The advantage of playing at home versus on the road.
Injuries and Suspensions: The impact of injuries and suspensions on each team's lineup.
Recent Performance (30%)
Recent Games: Each team's performance over their last 5-10 games.
By incorporating home and away splits into the rating system, you can gain a more nuanced understanding of each team's strengths and weaknesses.


To predict NHL over/under matchups within 70% accuracy, you'll need a combination of statistical analysis, team performance metrics, and betting trends. Here's a simplified value system to get you started:
Team Performance Metrics: Analyze teams' recent performance, including goals for and against, power-play percentage, and penalty kill percentage. Websites like OddsTrader provide detailed NHL odds and statistics ¹.
Head-to-Head Matchups: Study the teams' past matchups, including their scoring trends and any notable injuries or suspensions.
Betting Trends: Look at public betting percentages and sharp money indicators. SportsBettingDime provides NHL public betting trends and analysis ².
Injuries and Suspensions: Keep an eye on injured reserve lists and suspended players, as these can significantly impact a team's performance.
Home and Away Records: Consider teams' home and away records, as some teams perform significantly better in their own arena.
Recent Form: Analyze teams' recent form, including their last 5-10 games. This can help identify trends and patterns.
By combining these factors, you can develop a value system to predict NHL over/under matchups. However, keep in mind that no system is foolproof, and upsets can occur. Always bet responsibly and within your means.
if you look at the nhl game data from 2021 until today and internet or facebook, what arte some factors that cause an upset
Analyzing NHL game data from 2021 to present, along with internet and social media trends, reveals several factors that contribute to upsets:
Team-Related Factors
Injuries to Key Players: Injuries to top scorers, goaltenders, or defensemen can significantly impact a team's performance.
Goaltender Performance: A hot or cold streak by a goaltender can greatly influence a team's chances of winning.
Team Fatigue: Teams playing their third game in four nights or fourth game in six nights may experience fatigue, leading to an upset.
Coaching Changes: A recent coaching change can lead to an adjustment period, causing a team to underperform.
Opponent-Related Factors
Underdog Motivation: Teams with nothing to lose or seeking revenge for a previous loss may be more motivated to cause an upset.
Opponent's Recent Performance: A team on a hot streak may be due for a regression, while a team on a cold streak may be due for a bounce-back.
Head-to-Head Matchups: Teams with a history of success against their opponent may have an edge, while teams with a poor record against their opponent may struggle.
External Factors
Travel and Scheduling: Teams traveling across time zones or playing games with short rest may be at a disadvantage.
Weather and Road Conditions: Inclement weather or poor road conditions can impact travel and team preparation.
Social Media and Public Pressure: Teams facing intense public scrutiny or social media pressure may feel added stress, leading to an upset.
In-Game Events: Events like fights, ejections, or controversial calls can shift momentum and impact the outcome of a game.
Advanced Statistics
Corsi and Fenwick: Teams with a high Corsi (shots attempted) or Fenwick (unblocked shots attempted) may be more likely to win, even if they're the underdog.
Expected Goals: Teams with a high expected goals (xG) value may be more likely to score, even if they're the underdog.
Goalie Save Percentage: Teams facing a goalie with a high save percentage may struggle to score, while teams facing a goalie with a low save percentage may have an easier time scoring.
Keep in mind that upsets can occur due to a combination of these factors or unexpected events. Always bet responsibly and within your means.
